        "content": "<p>Is there not a <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Set.subset_def#doc\">docs#Set.subset_def</a> lemma?</p>",
        "id": 514637527,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1745753779
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Indeed it's that one. <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"819062\">@Lauri Oksanen</span> in general you are not really supposed to unfold definitions (especially for very basic objects) but rather use their attached API, such as the lemma <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"307953\">@Ruben Van de Velde</span> pointed out. Unfolding will often result in nasty looking stuff, and is also quite brittle as a strategy, as the details of definitions are liable to change often (to something mathematically equivalent of course). Aside from being a good coding practice it's good mathematics, thinking in terms of universal properties and so on</p>",
        "id": 514638286,
